A debounce function limits the rate at which a function can be invoked, ensuring that it only runs after a specified delay since the last time it was called.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
    let timeoutId;
    return function(...args) {
        clearTimeout(timeoutId);
        timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
            func.apply(this, args);
        }, delay);
    };
}

// Example usage:
const logResize = () => {
    console.log('Window resized!');
};

const debouncedResize = debounce(logResize, 300);

window.addEventListener('resize', debouncedResize);
```

In this example, the `logResize` function is debounced so that it only logs "Window resized!" after the user has stopped resizing the window for 300 milliseconds.
